{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S6 1ba5: Docs — private-repo credentials, descriptive errors, ref/source semantics, HMAC trust model); 4-bucket audit against the WHOLE EIGHT-child roster]\n\nVERDICT: EMPTY G3 findings list. The union of the eight children (S1 6d56 materialize core, S2 70c7 cache read/populate, S2b b73c janitor, S3 fa49 gate threading, S4 30b3 attested signing, S4b e308 claim-gate coherence/ADR 0002, S5 b7fa CLI/MCP surfaces, S6 1ba5 THIS docs) covers every parent acceptance/success criterion; no uncovered parent criterion is attributable to this pairing.\n\n4-bucket coverage map (parent AC -> covering child/children; THIS child's role + bucket):\n\n- Parent AC1 (no code-reading gate reads the server working tree in attested mode; all read a faithful snapshot at the pinned SHA) — FULLY covered by S1 (materialize core) + S3 (gate re-rooting). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. THIS docs child (Scope: \"Out: code (S1-S5)\"); it documents the behavior, doesn't implement it. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC2 (signed verdict binds verified_at_sha via the signed manifest channel; reproducible; no payload-schema/version change; prior signatures verify) — implementation FULLY by S4 atop S1's immutable-SHA basis. THIS child DOCUMENTS the attested-signs / verified_at_sha-recording semantics (its AC3) and the HMAC trust model + in-toto Statement shape (its AC4). Documentation slice owned here; mechanism owned by S4. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC3 (local source mode reads in-place checkout AND cannot produce a signed verdict; source=local is the documented back-out that restores prior in-place read behavior) — covered SPLIT: S3 reads-in-place, S4 bars-signing, and THIS child DOCUMENTS the signs-vs-never-signs + the fail-closed(attested)/local-still-runs behavior (its AC2) and the ref/source semantics incl. the origin/main default (its AC3). The \"documented back-out\" clause has its doc home here (reinforced by S3's own advisory AC). Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC4 (concurrent gates without git-lock contention / cross-op corruption; cache + janitor reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark without disrupting in-flight reads) — implementation FULLY by S1 + S2 + S2b. THIS child documents the disk-cap behavior (its AC5). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. the concurrency mechanism. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC5 (private-repo fetch failure surfaces a descriptive, actionable credential error) — covered SPLIT: S1 RAISES the actionable error (its AC5, attested fails closed); THIS child is the PRIMARY OWNER of the DOCUMENTATION half — its AC1 (README MCP-setup section + docs/jira-sync-setup.md state the private-repo fetch-credential requirement and how to supply it, grep-able) + its AC2 (the descriptive missing-credential error message + remedy and the fail-closed-vs-local-still-runs behavior documented in a named file). The parent's \"descriptive, actionable credential error\" obligation has its operator-facing guidance home precisely here. Clean behavior(S1)/docs(S6) split. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC6 (portable across macOS + Linux: no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback) — implementation FULLY by S1. THIS child documents the operator-facing portability surface — REBAR_GATE_TMPDIR + the EFS/NFS flock caveat (xref alto-fruit-punch) (its AC5). Behavior(S1)/docs(S6) split; the no-tar/no-/tmp/flock-fallback impl sub-clauses are S1's, not re-owned here. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC7 (operational tunables — free-space watermark, default ref, grace/age windows — configurable with documented defaults, S2/S3) — covered SPLIT: the tunables themselves are owned by S2b (watermark + grace/max-age, b73c AC9) and S3 (default ref/source via standard rebar config + REBAR_* precedence); THIS child is the PRIMARY OWNER of the \"DOCUMENTED defaults\" half — REBAR_GATE_TMPDIR + disk-cap behavior documented in named files (its AC5), and the ref/source + origin/main default documented (its AC3). The parent's \"with documented defaults\" clause lands here. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent AC8 (an ADR captures the architecture + rejected alternatives — PID-lease, payload-schema SHA binding) — ADR authoring owned by S2/S2b (cache/janitor architecture + rejected PID+heartbeat lease, b73c AC10), S4 (manifest-vs-payload SHA-binding decision, 30b3 AC1), and S4b (ADR 0002, e308). THIS child carries the HMAC trust-model + in-toto-Statement-shape DOCS (its AC4), which is the user-facing trust-model documentation, distinct from the architecture ADR. The ADR clauses each have a named owner in the roster; this child does not claim ADR authoring and need not. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child for the ADR itself. Not an absence.\n\n- Parent final AC (all EIGHT enumerated child stories closed; make lint + full test suite green) — STRUCTURAL/meta epic-completion criterion; covered by the existence of all eight children (this is S6 of 8) + each child's own green-bar obligation. Not an absence at this child.\n\nSuccess-criteria narrative — the parent's three success clauses (\"every gate verifies a client-specified, immutable, reproducible snapshot ... never the mutable checkout\"; \"signed verdicts bind verified_at_sha via the manifest channel\"; \"local preserves the single-developer verify-before-push workflow\") are implemented across S1-S5 and DOCUMENTED by THIS child: ref/source semantics + origin/main default + signs-vs-never-signs + verified_at_sha recording (its AC3), HMAC trust model + limits + in-toto shape (its AC4), the operational knobs + EFS/NFS caveat (its AC5), and the credential requirement + error behavior (its AC1/AC2). No uncovered obligation introduced by this child's existence; it adds no implementation criterion that another child must satisfy.\n\nNamed-consumer / delegation cross-checks (covered-by-named-consumer, not absences): this child explicitly scopes code OUT (\"Out: code (S1-S5)\") and documents what the named siblings implement — credential-raise -> S1 (6d56 AC5); signing/verified_at_sha + in-toto envelope -> S4 (30b3); ref/source threading + defaults -> S3 (fa49); CLI/MCP surfaces -> S5 (b7fa); disk-cap/tunables -> S2b (b73c). Each documented behavior is produced by a named sibling present in the roster. This child is itself the NAMED CONSUMER that S1/S3/S4 delegate their docs hand-offs to (S1's credential-error docs, S3/S4's local-mode + ref/source docs, S4's HMAC-trust-model + in-toto docs all name S6 as the doc owner; this child's AC1-AC5 claim each).\n\nNote (NOT a G3 finding): the standing G4 dependency-gap on S4/S4b (routing the pinned-SHA snapshot handle into plan_review/attest.py's hashing path) is a consistency/mechanism concern unrelated to this docs child; it does not bear on G3 union-coverage, which is complete.\n\nConclusion: this docs child cleanly OWNS the documentation slice of the parent criteria — primary owner of the documentation half of parent AC5 (credential requirement + error behavior), AC6 (REBAR_GATE_TMPDIR + EFS/NFS flock caveat docs), and AC7 (\"documented defaults\"), plus the ref/source-semantics and HMAC-trust-model/in-toto-shape user-facing docs that carry the parent's success-criteria narrative. Every parent acceptance/success criterion has a named owner in the eight-story roster; none is left uncovered. NO G3 finding for this pairing."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782534191661654001,"uuid":"6050fcbb-5061-4787-b3a2-179ea9bf878d"}